n, Stephen -- tPart Four. Futures at the End of Utopia -- tViktor Pelevin and Literary Postmodernism in Soviet Russia / rGomel, Elana -- tThe Forces of Kinship: Timur Bekmambetov's Night Watch Cinematic Trilogy / rStrukov, Vlad -- tThe Antiuopia Factory: The Dystopian Discourse in Russian Literature in the Mid-2000s / rChantsev, Aleksandr -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the dawn of the Space Age, when the Soviet Union launched the first artificial satellite and sent the first human into the cosmos, science fiction literature and cinema from Russia has fascinated fans, critics, and scholars from around the world. Informed perspectives on the surprisingly long and incredibly rich tradition of Russian science fiction, however, are hard to come by in accessible form. This critical reader aims to provide precisely such a resource for students, scholars, and the merely curious who wish to delve deeper into landmarks of the genre, discover innumerable lesser-known gems in the process, and understand why science fiction came to play such a crucial role in Russian society, politics, technology, and culture for more than a century. Contributors include: Mark B. Adams, Anindita Banerjee, Lynn Barker, Eliot Borenstein, Aleksandr Chantsev, Istvan Csicsery-Ronay, Stephen Dalton, Dominic Esler, Elana Gomel, Andrew Horton, Yvonne Howell, Asif A. Siddiqi, Robert Skotak, Michael G. Smith, Vlad Strukov, Darko Suvin  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aScience fiction filmszSoviet UnionxHistory and criticism. 0aScience fiction, RussianxHistory and criticism. 70(DE-601)1042532310(DE-588)4051038-4aRussisch2gnd 70(DE-601)1045985490(DE-588)4054021-2aScience-Fiction-Literatur2gnd 70(DE-601)1047574340(DE-588)4054023-6aScience-Fiction